<dl id="n54145i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54145i">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54145i"> 145(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Skull! <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54145i"><li>FW 25.22 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54145i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54145i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54145i">MS BL 47476b-468</ms> </li><li>JJA 50:274 <a name="ad8" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#ad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad8.htm#n54145i">Draft: I.1&sect;1.8</a>/2.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Poss&eacute;der le cr&acirc;ne d&apos;un ennemi, c&apos;est donc l&apos;avoir lui-m&ecirc;me en son pouvoir, souvent &agrave; son service. Garder par devers soi <mark>le cr&acirc;ne</mark> d&apos;un p&egrave;re ou d&apos;un chef, c&apos;est s&apos;assurer la facult&eacute; de lui parler, de lui demander conseil ou assistance, de s&apos;enqu&eacute;rir de ses &laquo;dispositions&raquo;, d&apos;apaiser sa col&egrave;re s&apos;il y a lieu, et de gagner sa faveur. <br><font color="green">[To possess the skull of an enemy is therefore to have him in his power, often in his service. Keeping the skull of a father or a chief in front of you is ensuring the ability to speak to him, to ask him for advice or assistance, to inquire about his "dispositions", to appease his anger if necessary, and gain his favor.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 200</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <i>Skol!</i>, a salute or a toast. </mm> </dd></dl>
